[1] Society Islands
Date: Thu 12 Mar 2009
Source: La Depeche de Tahiti [in French, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.tahitipresse.pf/index.cfm?snav=see&presse=26956>

Currently, Polynesia is "at the beginning of an
epidemic of dengue [virus] type 4" as was
announced yesterday [11 Mar 2009] by the Ministry
and the Directorate of Health. Since early 2009,
29 cases of confirmed dengue 4 (including 2
imported from New Caledonia) were recorded. Just
last week, 18 new cases of dengue type 4 [virus infection] were recorded.

[Of these dengue cases] 7 live in Bora Bora,
Tahaa 8, 2 in Tahiti and one in Moorea. Since 23
February [2009], 26 cases of dengue 4 [virus
infection] in total have been confirmed, mostly
in and Tahaa Bora Bora. The other cases of the
infection have traveled in other localities:
Faa'a, Moorea and Ua Pou. But so far, no
hospitalization or severe forms [of the disease]
have been reported, health authorities stated.
One should recall the instructions of the fight
against sources of mosquitoes, and especially in
case of onset of fever, headache, aches, signs
suggestive dengue it is advisable to consult your
doctor or nearest health facility more quickly.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 12 Mar 2009 report in Tahitipresse.fr (in
French)(<http://www.tahitipresse.pf/index.cfm?snav=see&presse=26956>)
indicated that dengue 1 virus was circulating in
the islands, too. For the week of 2-8 Mar [2009],
6 cases of dengue 1 virus infection and 18 cases
of dengue 4 virus infection have been laboratory
confirmed. Among these 18 cases of dengue 4 virus
infection, no epidemiological link was found
between them. The report goes on to state that in
the Pacific region, epidemic dengue 4 is still
rampant. If the number of cases begins to decline
in the 1st countries affected (Kiribati, Vanuatu,
Cook Islands ...), it increases in New Caledonia.

In this country, dengue so far has affected 3189
people and caused 2 deaths since September 2008.
Currently, more than 1500 cases of dengue fever
per month have been recorded, the majority of
cases of dengue being due to dengue virus 4, but also to dengue virus 1.

A map showing the location of the Society Islands
in the South Pacific and the main islands in the group can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/oceania/society.htm>. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Sri Lanka
Date: Thu 12 Mar 2009
Source: China View
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-03/12/content_10999066.htm>


More than 2000 Sri Lankans have been caught by
dengue fever this year [2009], representing a 15
percent increase compared to the same period of
2008, health experts said Thursday [12 Mar 2009].
Officials from the Epidemic Unit of the Health
Ministry said that 2229 people acquired dengue
[virus infection] from the beginning of this year
[1 Jan 2009] to 9 Mar 2009 while 17 people died of the disease.

They said the death cases increased sharply this
year as only 25 people were killed by dengue
[virus infection] in the island in 2008. The
capital Colombo is a badly affected area with 5
people having died of the epidemic so far this year [2009].

According to medical officials, there are 2 peak
seasons for the spreading of the epidemic in Sri
Lanka each year: one is from October to December;
another is from May to July. The government has
asked the public to clean the environment and
destroy all possible hatchery sites of mosquitoes
which are the carriers of the dengue viruses.

[Byline: Zhang Xiang, Editor]

--
