[4] Trinidad
Date: Thu 12 Mar 2009
Source: Trinidad and Tobago's Newsday [edited]
<http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,96518.html>


The number of reported dengue cases for central
Trinidad has begun to climb. Data obtained from a
medical source in the Chaguanas area indicated
there were "92 plus cases" reported from public
and private facilities for the last 3 months.
This figure was described as "slightly higher than normal."

The trend was corroborated by the Chaguanas Mayor
Surujrattan Rambachan who said information he
received was that there was an average of 100
cases for the 1st 2 and one-half months of this
year [2009]. He said there was one suspected
death in the Charlieville area and a Piarco resident was hospitalised with DHF.

Despite a media blitz advising the public about
taking precautions to prevent dengue, last year
saw an increased number of dengue cases with some
persons saying there was an "outbreak." However,
the Health Ministry has insisted there was no
outbreak. In its 2008 End of Year Dengue Report,
the ministry had 3832 "identified, reported
cases" out of which 100 were "confirmed" by the
Trinidad Public Health laboratory. There were 6 confirmed deaths.

The Insect Vector Control Division of the
ministry dynafogged 102 986 houses and ULV [ultra
low volume] sprayed 417 148. Residual spraying was done at 9948.

--
