[6] Peru
Date: Tue 10 Mar 2009
Source: Xinhua net [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-03/10/content_10981516.htm>


Peru registered 5000 cases of dengue fever during
January and February [2009], which has become a
public health problem, Health Minister Oscar
Ugarte said on Monday [9 Mar 2009]. Ugarte told
the press that 13 500 people were infected last
year [2008]. He announced the launching of a
campaign against dengue designed to raise public
awareness of the importance of clearing stagnant
water or hidden water deposits where the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito, a dengue [virus] carrier,
breeds. "We have an enormous responsibility to
combat dengue because it is lethal ... a high
social cost on human lives," Ugarte said.

He said combating dengue was easy. Daily actions
were needed to avoid water stagnating in topless
containers, and replacing water in flowerpots
with humid sand both at home and at public
places. Ugarte also called on Peruvians to clear
roofs or yards of tires, empty bottles or boxes
where rainwater can accumulate. "It is a national
campaign. If we do not take measures now, we will have an epidemic," he said.

[Byline: Xiong Tong, Editor]

--
Communicated by:
Healthmap Alerts via
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[While it is theoretically easy to reduce water
catchments in which _Aedes aegypti_ breed, it is
obviously difficult to do in practice, as
reflected in the dengue epidemics that occur
annually, despite campaigns to involve the
public. However, any effort to reduce the
populations of these vectors is worth doing.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Peru
can be accessed at <http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-9.2,-75.9,5>. - Mod.TY]

