[8] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Wed 11 Mar 2009
Source: Estadao [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY]
<http://www.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,ba-confirma-14-mortes-por-dengue-hemorragica-no-ano,337038,0.htm>


Between January and the end of February this year
[2009], 14 people died -- victims of DHF in
Bahia. The situation is more worrying in Itabuna,
a city with more than 2000 reported cases of the
disease, according to information from the
Secretariat of Health. Just in the last 6 days,
in the Hospital de Base, 600 people were seen with symptoms of the disease.

In the city, there now have been 5 deaths
confirmed by laboratory tests, according to the
Secretariat. Between this past Monday and Tuesday
[9-10 Mar 2009], 2 other deaths suspected to have
occurred from the diseases have not been confirmed by the Secretariat.

Throughout the state, 15 395 dengue fever cases
have been reported, 208 percent above last year
[2008]. An additional 123 cases are DHF.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[9] Paraguay
Date: Sun 8 Mar 2009
Source: Los Tiempos [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.lostiempos.com/noticias/08-03-09/08_03_09_ultimas_vyf1.php>


The authorities of the Ministry of Health
reported today [8 Mar 2009] the detection of the
1st DHF case in Paraguay, where 368 people have
now suffered from the benign variety of the
disease so far this year. [As noted in comments
in previous updates, sufferers of classical
dengue "breakbone" fever would hardly term it "benign." - Mod.TY]

The official indicated that this more virulent
type of dengue, which can cause death, was
diagnosed in a man who resided in the Capiata
locality, 25 km [16 mi] east of Asuncion, and for
whom more information was not given.

According to the Ministry of Health, the majority
of the 368 cases of this disease, transmitted by
the bite of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, were
reported so far this year in the northern
department [state of province equivalent], along the border with Brazil.

The above mentioned agency moreover mentioned
that currently an average of 20 [dengue] infections per week were reported.

And another thing, Allende recalled that the
health authorities established a risk period for
transmission that could extend until this May
[2009], facilitated, according to the official,
by the rainy season which favors the proliferation of the mosquito vector.

Paraguay registered an epidemic outbreak in 2008
with 18 illnesses of the benign variety, while in
2007, dengue took the lives of 17 people, of a
total of 27 000 [dengue] infections.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

