[10] Argentina (northern)
Date: Fri 13 Mar 2009
Source: Datachaco.com [in Spanish, trans Mod. TY, edited]
<http://datachaco.com/noticia.php?numero=18202>


Mayor Hector Pallares stated that a significant
number of suspected [dengue] cases have been
detected. As in Seanz Pena, Campo Largo and
Charata, there is a national health team working
on preventive tasks. "It is something that is expanding," he said.

In statements made on the program "1st Light" on
The Radio 104.7, Pallares confirmed that Avia
Terai was also having a dengue outbreak, based on
a significant number of suspected cases
recognized lately. Although unwilling to give
numbers, the community head indicated that while
the Ministry of Health of the province says it
has to wait until results arrive from the
laboratory in Pergamino, the doctors and the people say it is dengue.

Also, Pallares acknowledged existing concern and
that there is a national health team working in
the locality, on preventive measures such as
fumigation and consciousness raising of the
people so that they take necessary measures. "It
is necessary that everyone, the national
government, the province, the municipality and
the neighbors, work on prevention."

In addition, the mayor noted that he maintains
constant contact with his counterpart from Campo
Largo, Juan Carlos Fariello, in order to know the
situation in other locations where dengue cases
are occurring. "This is something that began in
Campo Largo and is spreading throughout the province," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the 7 Mar 2009 report by Yahoo Noticias (in
Spanish)
<http://es.noticias.yahoo.com/9/20090307/tsc-ya-son-dos-los-muertos-por-dengue-he-539a483.html>,
posted by ProMED-ESP, the 1st DHF death occurred
in Salto. The Salto government has declared a
medical emergency in 3 of its departments; Oran,
San Martin and Rivadavia, to prevent an outbreak.
These 3 departments are along the Bolivian
border, a country with a serious dengue outbreak
currently. The Argentina health authorities are
carrying out control actions in order to slow the
epidemic after finding locally acquired cases in
the northwest part of the country. There have
been 74 of these confirmed locally acquired cases
and 420 cases associated epidemiologically as
well as 144 cases imported from other areas.
Mod.JRT commented, "The occurrence of high
mortality rates during the 1st appearance of a
DHF outbreak in a region,when the primary health
care workers are not completely familiarized with
the management of these severe forms of the
infection, is not unusual. The fatality rates
observed in Latin American countries where dengue
presents a recurrent problem, varies between 0.15
- 0.30 per 1000 reported cases. If we consider
the fact that these notified cases always
represent an important under-reported real number
[of dengue cases] it is estimated that for every
reported dengue case there are between 10 - 20
undiagnosed cases), the expected fatality rate would be considerably less."

A map of Argentina showing the provinces
mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol_1996.pdf>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of
Argentina can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=-35.4,-64.2,5>. - Mod.TY]
